message.content:
To align a row of `div` elements to the right using Flexbox in CSS, you can use the following code snippet as an example:

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Flexbox Example</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="flex-container">
        <div class="flex-item">Item 1</div>
        <div class="flex-item">Item 2</div>
        <div class="flex-item">Item 3</div>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS (styles.css):
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

.flex-container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: flex-end; /* This line aligns the items to the right */
}

.flex-item {
    background-color: lightblue;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 5px;
    border-radius: 5px;
}
```

In this example, we have a container with three `div` elements inside it. The parent container has the class "flex-container", and its display property is set to "flex". The child elements have the class "flex-item" and are aligned to the right using the `justify-content: flex-end;` property. This will push all items to the right side of the container.

You can customize the appearance of the items by adjusting the CSS properties in the `.flex-item` class. Make sure to link the styles.css file to your HTML document using the `<link>` tag inside the `<head>` section.

Remember that Flexbox is supported in modern browsers, but you can use a fallback solution for older browsers if needed.
